{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T14-46-56-840Z","slug":"semantic-vector-search-landscape","locale":"es","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T14:47:20.236Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2026-05-01--semantic-vector-search-landscape/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2026-05-01--semantic-vector-search-landscape/es/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/semantic-vector-search-landscape/es/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T14-46-56-840Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"572f632a4fafd980b89c8a3904ef4f531468c50aac3fa5a9debce113dd6202a8","outputHash":"09fb20d7ff698114dbae1da66257cb2d26a0da0a9ae62332fc9d03961f08aad2","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary**  \nThe article argues that semantic (vector) search is a complementary layer—not a universal replacement—for traditional lexical, fuzzy, and exact‑match techniques. It explains how embeddings turn text (or other media) into high‑dimensional vectors, how HNSW indexes enable fast approximate nearest‑neighbor lookup, and how methods like RRF can fuse vector and full‑text results. The piece outlines concrete scenarios where pgvector shines—retrieval‑augmented generation, intent‑driven queries, similarity‑based recommendation, deduplication, and multilingual retrieval—while warning that vectors always return a result and must be thresholded. Written in a pragmatic, tutorial‑style tone for engineers and architects building search systems (especially PostgreSQL users), it repeatedly frames the discussion with the metaphor of “choosing the right tool from a toolbox” and emphasizes a hybrid architecture rather than “embed everything.”","totalInputTokens":19044,"totalOutputTokens":7728,"totalCacheReadTokens":3072,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":21509,"totalCostUsd":0.002133756,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro